# Deploying to Flying Fox

When the user mentions **deploying**, **publishing**, or **hosting** their static site, guide them to use the **fox** CLI tool for Flying Fox hosting.

## What is Fox?

Fox (`@canva-ct/fox`) is a CLI tool for deploying static sites to Flying Fox hosting at `*.flyingfox.canva-experiments.com`. It provides both interactive and non-interactive deployment modes.

## IMPORTANT: Cursor/Claude Code Usage

**When deploying from Cursor, ALWAYS use non-interactive commands:**

- ❌ NEVER run `npx fox` (interactive mode) - it won't work in Cursor
- ✅ ALWAYS run `npx fox deploy --project-name <name>` with an explicit project name
- ✅ ALWAYS use `npx fox auth --auto` (never `npx fox auth`) for authentication

**You MUST ask the user for a project name if one isn't already configured.**

### Required Workflow for Cursor

1. Check auth: `npx fox info`
2. If not authenticated: `npx fox auth --auto`
3. Check project config: Look for `.fox/config.json` or run `npx fox info`
4. If no project name: **ASK THE USER** (don't guess or make up a name)
5. Build: `npm run build`
6. Deploy: `npx fox deploy --project-name <user-provided-name>`

## Deployment Workflow (For Cursor/Claude Code)

When a user asks to deploy, follow this **exact workflow**:

### Step 1: Check Authentication Status

First, run `npx fox info` to check if the user is already authenticated:

```bash
npx fox info
```

### Step 2: Authenticate if Needed

If the user is not logged in, use **automatic authentication** (required for Cursor):

```bash
npx fox auth --auto
```

This will:

- Open their browser for OAuth authentication
- Save the token to `~/.fox/config.json`
- Exit automatically after authentication completes

### Step 3: Determine Project Name

Check if a project name is already configured:

- Look for `.fox/config.json` in the project directory
- Run `npx fox info` to see if a project is configured

**If no project name exists:**

- **STOP and ASK THE USER** what they want to name their project
- Do NOT guess or make up a project name
- Explain: "This will be deployed to https://[username]-[project-name].flyingfox.canva-experiments.com/"

Example questions:

- "What would you like to name this project for deployment?"
- "What project name should I use? (It will be deployed to https://[username]-[project-name].flyingfox.canva-experiments.com/)"

### Step 4: Build the Project

Ensure the project is built before deploying:

```bash
npm run build
```

### Step 5: Deploy with Project Name

**ALWAYS use the non-interactive deploy command:**

```bash
npx fox deploy --project-name <the-project-name>
```

**NEVER run just `npx fox` in Cursor - it will not work!**

## Installation

If fox is not installed, it will be automatically run via npx. For local installation:

```bash
npm install @canva-ct/fox --save-dev
```

## Available Commands

### Non-Interactive Commands (Use These in Cursor)

```bash
npx fox deploy --project-name my-app        # Deploy with saved token (REQUIRED in Cursor)
npx fox auth --auto                         # Automatic authentication (REQUIRED in Cursor)
npx fox auth -a                             # Shorthand for --auto
npx fox info                                # Show auth status and project info
npx fox open                                # Open deployed site in browser
npx fox logout                              # Clear saved credentials
```

### Interactive Mode (Terminal/Manual Use Only - NOT for Cursor)

```bash
npx fox                                     # Interactive UI (does NOT work in Cursor)
npx fox auth                                # Interactive authentication (does NOT work in Cursor)
```

**Note:** Interactive commands (`npx fox` and `npx fox auth`) will not work when called from Cursor/Claude Code. Always use the non-interactive versions above.

## Command Flags

- `--project-name <name>` - Project name for deployment
- `--token <token>` - Authentication token (skips browser login)
- `--auto` / `-a` - Automatic authentication mode (no interactive UI)
- `--help` - Show help message

## Configuration Files

- **Global auth**: `~/.fox/config.json` (stores authentication token)
- **Project config**: `./.fox/config.json` (stores last deployed project per directory)

## Deployment URL Pattern

Sites are deployed to:

```
https://[username]-[project-name].flyingfox.canva-experiments.com/
```

## When to Suggest Fox

Suggest using fox when the user:

- Asks about deploying their app/site
- Mentions Flying Fox hosting
- Wants to publish their static files
- Needs to update an existing deployment
- Is working with `dist/` or `build/` folders
- Mentions drag-and-drop deployment (fox is faster!)

## Tips for Cursor/Claude Code

1. **Authentication**: Always use `npx fox auth --auto` (never `npx fox auth`)
2. **Project name required**: Always provide `--project-name` when deploying
3. **Ask when needed**: If no project is configured, ask the user for a name before deploying
4. **Subsequent deployments**: Run `npx fox deploy --project-name <name>` - it remembers your token
5. **Quick access**: After deploying, use `npx fox open` to view the site

## Example Complete Workflow (For Cursor)

```bash
# 1. Check auth status
npx fox info

# 2. If not logged in, authenticate (non-interactive)
npx fox auth --auto

# 3. Check if project is configured
npx fox info

# 4. If no project name, ASK THE USER for one (don't guess!)
# Then proceed with the name they provide

# 5. Build the project
npm run build

# 6. Deploy with explicit project name (REQUIRED)
npx fox deploy --project-name my-awesome-app

# 7. Open deployed site
npx fox open
```

## Common Issues & Solutions

- **"No dist or build folder found"**: Make sure you've built your project first with `npm run build`
- **Authentication expired**: Run `npx fox auth --auto` to re-authenticate (never `npx fox auth`)
- **Wrong project name**: Check `./.fox/config.json` or run `npx fox info`
- **Token issues**: Run `npx fox logout` then `npx fox auth --auto` to get a fresh token
- **Command hangs/doesn't respond**: You probably ran `npx fox` or `npx fox auth` instead of the non-interactive versions. These don't work in Cursor!
- **No project configured**: Don't guess - ask the user what name they want for their project

